Before you can update firmware you must respect how flash physically behaves. Flash is **erase-before-write**: a programmed bit can only go 1->0 by writing; to set bits back to 1 you must **erase**, and erase works at a coarse **page/sector** granularity (often 2-128 KB), not per byte. You cannot rewrite a word in place; you erase its whole page first. Flash also has finite **endurance** (often ~10k-100k erase cycles per sector), so frequently-changing data needs **wear leveling** or EEPROM emulation rather than hammering one page. Many parts also forbid **read-while-write**: code cannot execute from the same flash bank you are erasing/programming, which is exactly why update code often runs from RAM or a second bank.

A **bootloader** is a small program that runs first and decides what to launch. The boot flow is layered: the on-chip **ROM bootloader** (mask ROM) runs at reset, optionally enters a vendor download mode, then hands control to *your* bootloader in flash, which validates and launches the **application**.

The jump to the app is the part people get wrong and brick boards. The app is built to a higher flash offset with its own vector table, so the bootloader must, in order: (1) **set the Vector Table Offset Register (VTOR)** to the app's vector table so interrupts dispatch into the app; (2) load the app's **initial stack pointer** from word 0 of its vector table into MSP; (3) load the **reset handler address** from word 1; (4) jump (branch) to it. Skipping VTOR or the SP load is the classic anti-pattern in the pitfalls list.

```c
#define APP_BASE 0x08008000u
void jump_to_app(void) {
    uint32_t sp   = *(volatile uint32_t *)(APP_BASE + 0);
    uint32_t rst  = *(volatile uint32_t *)(APP_BASE + 4);
    __disable_irq();
    SCB->VTOR = APP_BASE;            /* relocate vector table */
    __set_MSP(sp);                  /* set stack pointer     */
    __DSB(); __ISB();
    ((void (*)(void))rst)();        /* set PC: jump to app   */
}
```

A field firmware update is a transaction that must be **atomic** and **recoverable**: power can fail at any instant and the device must still boot. The robust pattern is built on the A/B (dual-bank) layout: an immutable bootloader plus a currently-running **active** slot and an **inactive** slot for staging.

The flow has four phases. **(1) Receive** the new image over a transport--UART, USB (often USB-DFU), or an OTA radio link--writing it into the *inactive* bank while the active app keeps running. **(2) Validate** before trusting it: check a **CRC** for integrity against corruption, and a cryptographic **signature** against a baked-in public key for authenticity (the heart of **secure boot** and the chain of trust). Reject and erase on any mismatch--never jump to an unverified image. **(3) Swap atomically**: set a small persistent flag/trailer to 'pending', reset, and let the bootloader make the inactive bank active. Because the *active* image is never overwritten in place, a power loss mid-update leaves the old working image intact--this is the anti-brick guarantee. **(4) Confirm or roll back**: the new image must run a self-test and explicitly **confirm** (set 'confirmed'); if it crashes or a boot-counter/watchdog expires before confirming, the bootloader **reverts** to the previous slot on the next reset.

You rarely write all this from scratch. **MCUboot** is the standard open bootloader (used by Zephyr) implementing signed images, swap/overwrite, and confirm/revert; **ESP-IDF OTA** provides `esp_ota_*` APIs over its `ota_0`/`ota_1` partitions with a rollback option; ST and others ship built-in DFU/secure-boot stacks. **Versioning** (monotonic version + anti-rollback counter) prevents downgrade attacks and accidental loops.

```c
if (!crc_ok(slotB) || !sig_verify(slotB, pubkey)) {
    flash_erase(slotB);          /* reject: keep running A */
} else {
    set_update_flag(PENDING);    /* bootloader swaps on reset */
    NVIC_SystemReset();
}
/* New image, once healthy: confirm; else watchdog -> revert to A */
```
